\implies \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} = 0.$ The only vector this includes that is perpendicular to $\mathbf{w}$ in particular is $\mathbf{w}\perp\mathbf{n}$. But if $\mathbf{w}$, $\mathbf{n}$ are both perpendicular then in particular consider $\alpha\| \mathbf{w}\| \mathbf{u}$ for any unit vector $\mathbf{u}$ giving that $c_{\alpha}= \| \mathbf{w} \|\ge1$ since $\mathbf{w}$ is not the zero vector. But if $\mathbf{n} = \mathbf{w}$ we then simply need to consider the plane generated by $\mathbf{r}$ such that this vector is perpendicular in particular we see then that $0=\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{r} = \mathbf{w} \cdot \mathbf{r} = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & -3\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y\\ z \end{pmatrix}=x-3z$ solving this for $x$ gives that the plane is given by $x=3z$ in which case the plane can be written as $x-3z=0$ which in turn takes the form $Ax+By+Cz+D=0$ with $A=1$, $B=0$, $C=-3$ and $D=0$, since the $gcd(|A|,|B|,|C|,|D|) = \gcd(1,0,3,0) = 1 > 0$ as required.
